<body>

<p>Like any other line, the equation of the least-squares regression line for summarizing the linear
   relationship between the
   response<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140428-0400"?> variable<?oxy_insert_end?>
   <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140431-0400"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>Y<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140432-0400"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
   and the explanatory <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140435-0400"?>variable
   (<?oxy_insert_end?>X<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140441-0400"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
   has the form: <m:math overflow="scroll">
    <m:mrow>
     <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
     <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
     <m:mo>=</m:mo>
     <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
     <m:mi>a</m:mi>
     <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
     <m:mo>+</m:mo>
     <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
     <m:mi>b</m:mi>
     <m:mi>X</m:mi>
    </m:mrow>
   </m:math>
  </p>
<p>All we need to do is calculate the intercept <em>a</em>, and the slope <em>b</em>, which is easily done if we know:
		</p>
<ul>
<li>
    <m:math overflow="scroll">
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mover>
       <m:mi>X</m:mi>
       <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
      </m:mover>
     </m:mrow>
    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140521-0400"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140518-0400" content=" - "?>the
    mean of the explanatory variable's values</li>
<li>
    S<sub>X</sub><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140537-0400"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140534-0400" content=" - "?>the
    standard deviation of the explanatory variable's values</li>
<li>
    <m:math overflow="scroll">
     <m:mrow>
      <m:mover>
       <m:mi>Y</m:mi>
       <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
      </m:mover>
     </m:mrow>
    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140544-0400"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140541-0400" content=" - "?>the
    mean of the response variable's values</li>
<li>
    S<sub>Y</sub><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140555-0400"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140551-0400" content=" - "?>the
    standard deviation of the response variable's values</li>
<li>
    r<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140604-0400"?>&#8212;<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140602-0400" content=" - "?>the
    correlation coefficient</li>
</ul>

<p><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140620-0400" content="It turns out that g"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101101T140627-0400"?>G<?oxy_insert_end?>iven
   the five quantities above, the slope and intercept of the least squares regression line are found
   using the following formulas: </p>
<ul>
<li>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>b</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mi>r</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
<m:mfrac>
<m:msub>
<m:mi>S</m:mi>
<m:mi>Y</m:mi>
</m:msub>
<m:msub>
<m:mi>S</m:mi>
<m:mi>X</m:mi>
</m:msub>
</m:mfrac>
</m:mfenced>
</m:mrow>
</m:math>
</li>
<li>
<m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>a</m:mi>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mo>=</m:mo>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mover>
<m:mi>Y</m:mi>
<m:mo>¯</m:mo>
</m:mover>
<m:mtext> </m:mtext>
<m:mo>−</m:mo>
